At some point I had to prioritize some things so that not only the reader wouldn't get burned out, but that I wouldn't get burned out as well. If you re-read Underneath you can tell I'm getting impatient at the end because I'm bolting for the finish line to get to the emotional climax, which is what I wanted to write all along in the first place.
I'm well aware of the story's problems (at least what I think are actual problems). I'm fine with Anon being as autistic as he is because it's clear his obsession is not healthy in the slightest. I drew on my own experience fighting these type of people in tournaments (and being that type of person as well, still kinda am).It's single mindedness to the point of being mental poison. All in all that story is about someone learning to become an actual person.

Personally in terms of the story's issues, it's one of the least egregious and I'd rate it my second best story because I played it safe for the most part and added my own little twist to the /hmofa/ formula. "Eden's Odyssey" and "Have You Seen the News?" experiments more and as a result have more issues of plot contrivances for the sake of an emotional payoff. Out of two, I think "Eden's Odyssey" is the better, more focused story. HYSTN, despite a VERY good ending and a unique premise has so many fucking issues that it's a wonder people still look on it with fondness. I certainly don't.

Honor is a system of unwritten social rules that facilitate smoother social interaction, and often certain social mobility, because people in the same society can be expected to hold the same ideas.

For instance, the ancient Greek system of honor included the culture of aristocrats being expected to provide a place to sleep for other aristocrats, as well as the culture of gift-giving attached to that. This allowed Greek aristocrats a high degree of mobility, allowing them to spread their ideas far and wide.
